---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About PlainProcedure"
  description="PlainProcedure makes healthcare procedure costs transparent using CMS Medicare data. Free, open data for patients and researchers."
>
  <section class="py-8 md:py-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About PlainProcedure</h1>
      <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--color-muted)] [&_h2]:text-[var(--color-foreground)] [&_strong]:text-[var(--color-foreground)]">
        <p>
          PlainProcedure makes healthcare costs transparent by showing what Medicare actually pays
          versus what providers charge for over 9,000 medical procedures. We help patients,
          researchers, and journalists understand price variation across states and providers.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Data</h2>
        <p>
          All data comes directly from the <strong>CMS Medicare Physician & Other Practitioners</strong>
          dataset for 2023. This includes:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>9,297 procedures:</strong> Every CPT/HCPCS code billed to Medicare, with national and state-level pricing</li>
          <li><strong>5,426 hospitals:</strong> CMS Hospital Compare data including quality ratings and emergency services</li>
          <li><strong>162,808 providers:</strong> Individual Medicare providers with their procedure volumes and charges</li>
          <li><strong>198,292 state-level price records:</strong> How procedure costs vary across 56 states and territories</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Methodology</h2>
        <p>
          We download raw datasets from CMS (data.cms.gov), process them through our ETL pipeline,
          and organize them into searchable pages. No data is modified, interpolated, or editorialized.
          Medicare payment amounts reflect the actual average amounts paid by Medicare for each procedure.
          Submitted charges reflect what providers bill (their "chargemaster" rates).
        </p>

        <h2>Understanding the Numbers</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Medicare Payment:</strong> What Medicare actually pays the provider. This is a standardized
          rate based on the procedure code and geographic adjustment factor.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Submitted Charge:</strong> What the provider bills (their list price). This is typically
          much higher than what any insurer pays. Uninsured patients may be billed closer to this amount.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Markup:</strong> The ratio between the submitted charge and Medicare payment. A 3.0x markup
          means the billed charge is 3 times the Medicare rate.
        </p>

        <h2>Updates</h2>
        <p>
          CMS releases updated Medicare provider data annually. We update our database when new
          data becomes available.
        </p>

        <h2>Not Affiliated</h2>
        <p>
          PlainProcedure is not affiliated with CMS, Medicare, or any government agency. We are
          an independent data portal providing public information in a more accessible format.
        </p>

<h2>How We Process the Data</h2>
        <p>
          We download the CMS Medicare Physician and Other Practitioners dataset and process each
          CPT/HCPCS code to extract national and state-level pricing. For every procedure, we calculate
          the markup ratio between submitted charges and Medicare payment amounts, revealing how much
          provider list prices diverge from what Medicare actually pays.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hospital profiles are enriched with CMS Hospital Compare quality ratings. Provider-level
          records show individual procedure volumes and charges. All payment figures represent actual
          Medicare-reported averages, not estimates or projections.
        </p><h2>Important Disclaimer</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>This site is for informational purposes only and does not provide medical advice.</strong>
          The data presented comes from government sources and is not a substitute for professional
          medical consultation. Medicare payment data represents averages and your actual costs may differ
          based on your insurance, provider, and specific circumstances. Always consult your healthcare
          provider and insurance company for actual pricing.
        </p>

        <h2>Contact</h2>
        <p>
          For questions or feedback, email <a href="mailto:hello@plainprocedure.com">hello@plainprocedure.com</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
